for this expirement we run all classifyers on test and train with same conditions all expirement done when:

  • tolorance is 5
  • train is 80% of train and test is 20% of train
  • all missing values are dealt by removing the row

The only change will be is the number of bins applyed and the binning strategy. Testing only the classifyers that require binning ('id3', 'naive_bayes', 'our_naive_bayes').
our_id3 not included due to very slow preformance of 'our_id3' classifyer

def plot_all_scores_in_row(data, function, strategy):
    print(function + " with " + strategy)
    data = data.copy()
    ### calculating the scores for the plot: ###
    number_of_bins = tuple(data['number of bins'].unique())
    for number in number_of_bins:
        tp = data.loc[data['number of bins']==number_of_bins,'TP']
        tn = data.loc[data['number of bins']==number_of_bins,'TN']
        fp = data.loc[data['number of bins']==number_of_bins,'FP']
        fn = data.loc[data['number of bins']==number_of_bins,'FN']
        # Accuracy = TP+TN/TP+FP+FN+TN
        data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'Accuracy'] = (tp + tn) / (tp + fp + fn + tn)
        # Precision = TP/TP+FP
        data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'Precision'] = tp / (tp + fp)
        # Recall = TP/TP+FN
        data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'Recall']  = tp / (tp + fn)
        # F1_Score = 2*(Recall * Precision) / (Recall + Precision)
        data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'F1_Score'] =  2 * (data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'Recall']  * data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'Precision']) /\
                                     (data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'Recall']  + data.loc[data['number of bins']==number,'Precision'])
    ####### ploting the data ###### 
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,5,figsize=(25, 5)) 

    # matrix #######################
    columns = ['TP','FP','TN','FN']
    values = data[columns]
    bars1 = values['TP'].to_list()
    bars2 = values['FN'].to_list()
    bars3 = values['TN'].to_list()
    bars4 = values['FP'].to_list()
    

    # Heights of bars1 + bars2
    bars_h1 = np.add(bars1, bars2).tolist()
    bars_h2 = np.add(bars_h1, bars3).tolist()

    # The position of the bars on the x-axis
    r = data['number of bins'].to_list()

    # bar width
    barWidth = 1

    # Create brown bars
    axes[0].bar(r, bars1, color='#fb5607', edgecolor='white', width=barWidth, label='TP')
    # Create green bars (middle1), on top of the second ones
    axes[0].bar(r, bars2, bottom=bars1, color='#3a86ff', edgecolor='white', width=barWidth, label='FN')
    # Create green bars (middle2), on top of the two first
    axes[0].bar(r, bars3, bottom=bars_h1, color='#ff006e', edgecolor='white', width=barWidth, label='TN')
    # Create green bars (top)
    axes[0].bar(r, bars4, bottom=bars_h2, color='#8338ec',  edgecolor='white' , width=barWidth, label='FP')
    # Custom X axis
    fig.tight_layout()
    ################################
    ### plting Accuracy,Precision,Recall,F1_Score #######
    colors = ('#9a031e', '#fb8b24', '#e36414', '#0f4c5c')
    for i,col in enumerate(['Accuracy','Precision','Recall','F1_Score']):
        sns.lineplot(x="number of bins", y=col, data=data, ax = axes[i+1], color=colors[i])  
    ################################
    plt.show()
    

functions = tuple(data['function'].unique())
strategies = tuple(data['strategy'].unique())
for i,function in enumerate(functions):
    for strategy in strategies:
        df = data.loc[(data['function'] == function) & (data['strategy'] == strategy)]
        plot_all_scores_in_row(df,function,strategy)
